<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="133" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1286,1889]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1722,1746]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Dworakowska, Nagaich &amp; Singh" authorityName="Dworakowska, Nagaich &amp; Singh" box="[624,1154,1721,1746]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Kapsa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simlensis">
<emphasis box="[624,762,1722,1746]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">K. simlensis</emphasis>
Dworakowska, Nagaich &amp; Singh
</taxonomicName>
, but has the apex of the paramere forked, the connective narrower, the aedeagal shaft curved ventrally and the preatrial process much shorter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="133" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1286,1889]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1830,1854]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin word “furcatus”, referring to the forked apex of the paramere.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
